{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01WcpTnchkrqV8NLRGpTBg8v","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to generate exactly 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files. Let me break down the requirements:\n\n1. Save to: tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.18.txt\n2. Filename rules:\n   - Use SPACES, not hyphens/underscores\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics\n   - Filename title must match the text content title\n\n3. Recipe mix: ~60% English (~6), ~40% Polish (~4)\n4. Variety: soups, mains, desserts, salads, appetizers, breads, drinks, preserves\n5. Mix of multi-word (2-5 words) and single-word titles\n\n6. MUST BE DIFFERENT from the long list provided\n\n7. Pattern requirements for this batch:\n   - 5 files with OCR_CORRUPTION: character corruption, digit for letter, dotless i, hyphenation artifacts, garbage tokens\n   - 3 files with NARRATIVE: 3-7 lines of prose intro between title and ingredients\n   - 2 files with COMPOUND: multiple recipes/variations in title\n\n8. File length: 15-60 lines (spillover files 40-60)\n\nLet me plan the 10 files:\n\n**English recipes (6):**\n1. Lemon Pound Cake - with OCR corruption\n2. Tomato Basil Pasta - with narrative\n3. Mushroom Risotto - with OCR corruption\n4. Chocolate Brownies + Fudgy Chocolate Brownies - COMPOUND with OCR corruption\n5. Roasted Brussels Sprouts - with narrative\n6. Summer Berry Tart - regular (no special pattern)\n\n**Polish recipes (4):**\n1. Żabka w Pomidorach - with OCR corruption\n2. Barszcz - with narrative (this is OK, different from \"Barszcz Czysty\")\n\n\n3. Kluski Pyrzane - with OCR corruption\n4. PIEROGI Z KAPUSTY : PIEROGI Z MIĘSEM - COMPOUND with narrative\n5. Żur Pszeniczny - regular\n\nWait, that's 11 total. I need to trim one recipe. Let me use \"Żur Pszeniczny\" instead of adding a fifth Polish option, keeping it at exactly 10 files with the pattern distribution intact: 5 corruption, 3 narrative, 2 compound.\n\nFor the OCR corruption group, I'll use Lemon Pound Cake, Żabka w Pomidorach, Mushroom Stroganoff, Kluski Pyrzane, and Blueberry Cheesecake. The narrative section will include Roasted Brussels Sprouts, Barszcz, and Salmon Teriyaki.\n\nThe compound files pair Chocolate Brownies with Fudgy Chocolate Brownies, and combine PIEROGI Z KAPUSTY with PIEROGI Z MIĘSEM. I'm checking each against the exclusion list—none of these recipes appear on it, though I note that Barszcz Czysty is excluded while plain Barszcz is acceptable.\n\nNow I'm generating OCR-corrupted text for each file, introducing realistic scanning artifacts like digit substitutions (só1 for sól), character confusion (rn for m, dotless ı), hyphenation breaks, and random garbage tokens to simulate imperfect document scanning. For the glaze, whisk together icing sugar and lemon juice until smooth, then pour over the cooled cake and top with lemon zest. The recipe yields 8-10 servings.\n\nThe remaining instructions cover the baking process: preheat to 180°C, cream the butter and sugar until light and fluffy, then incorporate the eggs, vanilla, and milk. Fold in the flour, salt, and lemon zest carefully before transferring to a greased loaf pan. Bake for 45-50 minutes until golden, then cool in the pan for 10 minutes before turning out onto a wire rack to cool completely.\n\nFor the glaze, I'll whisk together 200g icing sugar with 2-3 tablespoons of lemon juice until it reaches a thick paste consistency, then drizzle it over the cooled cake. Finish with lemon zest and thin strips of rind as garnish. The recipe yields 8-10 servings.\n\nNow I'm considering what realistic OCR errors to introduce—common mistakes include confusing the letter 'l' with the digit '1', 'rn' appearing instead of 'm', dropped diacritics, and scattered corrupted characters. I'll create multiple files with varying levels of corruption, using these patterns to make the errors feel authentic rather than random. for 45-50 minutes until golden and a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean. Once cooled slightly in the pan for about 15 minutes, turn it out onto a wire rack to cool completely.\n\nFor the glaze, whisk together icing sugar with lemon juice until smooth, then drizzle over the cooled cake and top with lemon zest. This recipe yields about 10 servings.\n\nThe frog legs are cleaned and prepared with garlic, canned tomatoes, white wine, olive oil, onion, salt, pepper, and mint. Heat oil over medium heat, sauté the onion and garlic briefly, then brown the frog legs on both sides before deglazing with wine and allowing it to reduce slightly. Add the tomatoes along with seasonings and mint, then simmer until the meat is tender—about 25 to 30 minutes—and serve alongside bread or rice.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":63871,"cache_read_input_tokens":15568,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":63871},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e799c0bb-71c9-46cb-a2f5-0d09a4801c74","uuid":"f55aaa21-68f2-4c4a-9d98-e2936ac51ce5"}
